==Notes==
<div class="references-small">
'''a.''' {{Note label|a|a|none}} J<U+00F3>zef Klemens Pi<U+0142>sudski was commonly referred to without his middle name, as "J<U+00F3>zef Pi<U+0142>sudski", A few English sources translate his first name as "Joseph", but this is not the common practice. As a young man, he belonged to underground organizations and used various pseudonyms, including "''Wiktor''", "''Mieczys<U+0142>aw''" and "''Ziuk''" (the latter also being his family nickname). Later he was often affectionately called "''Dziadek''" ("Grandpa" or "the Old Man") and "''Marsza<U+0142>ek''" ("the Marshal"). His ex-soldiers from the [[Polish Legions in World War I|Legions]] also referred to him as "''Komendant''" ("the Commandant").

'''b.''' {{Note label|b|b|none}}Pi<U+0142>sudski sometimes spoke of being a Lithuanian of Polish culture.<ref>[[#refDavies1986|Davies 1986]], p. 139.</ref> The question of his ethnicity and culture is not a simple one. [[Timothy Snyder]], who calls him a "Polish-Lithuanian", notes that Pi<U+0142>sudski did not think in terms of 20th-century nationalisms and [[ethnicity|ethnicities]]; he considered himself ''both'' a Pole and a Lithuanian, and his homeland was the historic [[Polish-Lithuanian Commonwealth]].<ref>[[#refSnyder2004|Snyder 2004]], p. 70.</ref> Discussing his role in Lithuania, ''[[Encyclop<U+00E6>dia Britannica]]'' describes him as a [[Polonized]] Lithuanian;<ref name="J<U+00F3>zef Klemens Pilsudski (president of Poland)<U+2014>Role in Lithuania: Baltic states. Lithuanian liberation"/> however, in the introduction to his biography it simply calls him "Polish".<ref name="J<U+00F3>zef Pilsudski"/> He is also described simply as "Polish" by the ''[[Columbia Encyclopedia]]''<ref>{{cite web
|url=http://www.encyclopedia.com/doc/1E1-Pilsudsk.html
|title=Joseph Pi<U+0142>sudski
|work=[[Columbia Encyclopedia]], Sixth Edition
|accessdate =17 December 2007
}}</ref> and ''[[Encarta]]''.<ref name="Encarta" />
</div>

